Re: withering vine<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Khasirath frowned as he looked at the Reaper, not wanting to believe what she was saying. She looked so strong, so achingly beautiful. He could not accept that she, of all people, could succumb to a coward’s poison. The very thought hurt him deeply. His gaze traced her delicate features, searching the eyes as violet as his own. Inside a chilling, tearing pain eclipsed his strength.<br>
<br>
When she made her request he thought his heart would stop. But looking into her eyes he knew there was nothing he could deny her – not even this. On his blade and his House he swore he would send her to Innoruuk if the poison affected her mind. He also swore he would do anything to find the cause and the cure, even lay down his life to save her own.<br>
<br>
Though his sister Tzanntiel was in training with the Ebon Mask, Khasirath knew little of poisons. Tzann had not yet earned their respect enough to be entrusted with such secrets. Struggling to understand where the poison was coming from Khasirath questioned the Reaper, looking for revelation and salvation.<br>
<br>
Her food and drink were tested, and she’d had her office and home gutted to remove any possible contamination, so Khasirath tried to think of other possibilities. He asked if she’d traveled to any new places in the time that the weakness had started, but she had not. Then he asked if she’d bought or found any new armour or weapons. After a moment’s thought she said that she’d recovered her Darkforge Greaves shortly before the first collapse.<br>
<br>
He knew that an undead Knight at the Temple of Solusek Ro made Darkforge from the remains of armours stolen by the Lizardmen of Cazic-Thule. He did not see how it could be related, but suggested that the Reaper have all her armour and weapons tested by her poison finders.<br>
<br>
She almost resisted, explaining that her armour and weapons were always with her, so no one could have tainted them. But Khasirath pointed out that because they were always with her, the effects would be greatest if that was where the poison was applied. He also told her to have it tested by an alchemist, as he had heard of metals that could sap the strength and health of even the strongest warrior.<br>
<br>
Though she seemed skeptical, the Reaper agreed. As he turned to leave, Khasirath wished her luck and the Father’s blessing. He also offered her the protection and hospitality of House S`Therik for as long as she might desire or require.<br>
<br>
The walk back to his House’s compound seemed too long, his mind full of darkness and pain. When he arrived he went directly to the House’s altar, kneeling down in his armour to pray for the strength of one of Innoruuk’s finest Knights. He also prayed that he would be allowed to visit the Father’s vengeance upon the poisoners, whomever they may be.<br>
<br>
Khasirath drank of the pain that welled through him, letting it reach every cell, every inch of himself, until his whole being seemed to shudder under it. Then he sent his mind deeper, to the wellspring of Hate, drawing it forth to meld with the pain. He harnessed the pain and the hate together, binding them so that they might make him stronger, and more focused. He willed this lash of pain-charged hate to be ready when he found the coward who would dare try to destroy the Reaper. <br>
<br>
Khasirath S'Therik. <br>
Knight of Innoruuk. <br>
